oc:kn_138ab877 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating or projecting referral program performance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Viral coefficient K > 1 means viral growth (each user brings >1 new user); K < 1 means amplified growth (referrals supplement other acquisition). K = Invitations × Conversion Rate." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The K-factor determines whether a referral program is self-sustaining or needs to be supplemented with other acquisition channels." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_1a1b6ecb a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing referral programs for products with low per-user value but high volume potential" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Tiered rewards with gamification (like Morning Brew's 3/5/10/25 referral tiers) drive ongoing engagement and turn referral into a repeatable activity rather than a one-time action." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Tiered structures give users escalating goals, increasing lifetime referral count and embedding sharing into the user's identity." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_1c3a3155 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When sizing referral rewards by business model" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Typical referral reward ranges: B2C $10-50 or 10-25% of first purchase; B2B SaaS $50-500 or 1-3 months free; Enterprise is higher and custom." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Market benchmarks prevent over- or under-incentivizing; rewards too high attract freebie-seekers, too low generate no participation." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_44843b84 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When calculating financial return of a referral program" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Referral Program ROI = (Revenue from referred customers - Program costs) / Program costs, where Program costs = Rewards paid + Tool costs + Management time." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Tracking ROI separately from other channels reveals the true economic value of the referral channel and justifies continued investment." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_8d2461f0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SuccessIndicator ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When measuring referral program health and setting targets" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Referral rate benchmarks: Good 10-25%, Great 25-50%, Exceptional 50%+. Referrals per referrer: Average 1-2, Good 2-5, Exceptional 5+." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These benchmarks allow you to assess whether your program is underperforming, meeting expectations, or exceptional compared to industry norms." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9ec9b936 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing any referral program incentive structure" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The most effective referral programs use double-sided incentives where both the referrer and the referred person benefit equally (e.g., Dropbox's give 500MB/get 500MB, Uber's give $10/get $10)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Double-sided incentives remove social friction — referrers don't feel like they're exploiting friends, and referred users feel welcomed rather than sold to." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f42b4752 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When determining how much to spend on referral incentives" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "formula" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Max Referral Reward = (Customer LTV × Gross Margin) - Target CAC. Example: LTV $1,200, margin 70%, target CAC $200 → max reward = $640." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ensures referral economics remain profitable by capping rewards at the actual economic value a referred customer generates minus what you'd otherwise spend to acquire them." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

